// @check
// @error expected i32, got any
// ANNOTATION RULE for forward/mutual calls: a function that is called BEFORE its
// own definition must declare its return type. The forward-reference pre-pass
// hoists `b`'s signature into module scope, but with no `: returnType` annotation
// its return is an inference hole (`any`) — and `b`'s body has not been checked
// yet at the point `a` calls it, so the hole cannot be filled. The call therefore
// resolves against `any` and `return b()` fails cleanly against `a`'s declared
// `i32` (no crash). This mirrors how an un-annotated *self*-recursive function
// already behaves. Annotate `b`'s return type (`function b(): i32`) to fix it.
function a(): i32 { return b() }
function b() { return 1 }
print(a())
